          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is bond yield?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Bond yield is the return an investor earns from holding a bond. The simplest measure is current yield, which is annual coupon income divided by the bond price. A more complete measure is yield to maturity (YTM), which is the internal rate of return that equates the present value of all future coupon and principal payments to the current market price."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is the difference between coupon rate and yield?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "The coupon rate is fixed in the bond contract and is calculated as annual coupon divided by face value. Yield is market-driv at a discount, yield is higher than the coupon rate; if it trades at a premium, yield is lower than the coupon rate."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "When should I look at yield to maturity vs current yield?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Use current yield when you only care about the income relative to price in the near term. Use yield to maturity when you plan to hold the bond until it matures and want a single annualized return figure that includes both coupon income and any capital gain or loss from buying at a discount or premium."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "What is yield to call and why is it important?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
              "text": "Yield to call (YTC) is the annualized return you would earn if a callable bond is redeemed by the issuer at the first call date instead of at final maturity. For callable bonds trading above par, YTC is often lower than YTM and can be a more realistic estimate of your return if rates fall and the issuer decides to call the bond."
            }
          },
          {
            "@type": "Question",
            "name": "Does this calculator assume annual or semiannual coupons?",
            "acceptedAnswer": {
              "@type": "Answer",
